# level2

This exercise is complicated.

First, we extract the C code and do the routine recognition of the binary.

The code structure is as follows:
```c
#include "out.h"

void p(void)
{
  uint unaff_retaddr;
  char local_50 [76];
  
  fflush(stdout);
  gets(local_50);
  if ((unaff_retaddr & 0xb0000000) == 0xb0000000) {
    printf("(%p)\n",unaff_retaddr);
    _exit(1);
  }
  puts(local_50);
  strdup(local_50);
  return;
}

void main(void)
{
  p();
  return;
}
```

We have a function `p` that checks:
```c
if ((unaff_retaddr & 0xb0000000) == 0xb0000000)
```
So we cannot do a direct function call back to stack memory.

Next, we have a `puts` and a `strdup`.
The `strdup` is the key. It duplicates our input onto the heap. This allows us to execute shellcode from the heap. Let's do the assembly recognition with GDB:

